ws of socialist aesthetics. By engaging with the relationship among culture, history, and politics in the context of the revolutionary transformation of Chinese society and arts, Cai illuminates the utopian promise as well as the ultimate impossibility of socialist cultural production. Translated, annotated, and edited by Rebecca E. Karl and Xueping Zhong, this translation presents Cai's influential work to English-language readers for the first time.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aChinese literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and culturezChina. 0aSocialism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh1 aKarl, Rebecca E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKarl, Rebecca E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZhong, Xueping, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZhong, Xueping, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374619zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374619.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles